20260507151928 Should this solution also work on Linux/MacOS?
20260507152045 Yes, with one important caveat to understand. Let me walk through each layer: mpv_ipc.py — yes, explicitly designed for it. The os.name == 'nt' guard routes Windows through the new _WinPipe ctypes path and leaves Unix going through the original socket.AF_UNIX + makefile('rwb', buffering=0) path. The deadlock we fixed is Windows-only — the CRT per-fd lock (_lock_fhandle) doesn't exist on Unix. Unix sockets support full-duplex concurrent reads/writes natively at the syscall level, and SocketIO (unbuffered RawIOBase) adds no Python-level lock on top. mpv_session.py / conftest.py — yes. os.path.abspath(), forward-slash paths, and mpv's --sub-file= flag all work identically on Linux/macOS. The IPC socket path auto-selects: \\.\pipe\... on Windows, /tmp/mpv-lls-test-.sock on Unix. Unit tests (run_unit.py, run_unit.lua) — yes. shutil.which('lua') finds the system Lua on any platform. The video fixture — binary file, platform-neutral. The only thing that won't work out of the box on Linux/macOS is the --ao=null flag if mpv is built without a null audio output (rare, but possible). A safe fallback is --ao=null which most mpv builds support. That's already what we use. So: no code changes needed for Linux/macOS. The platform-specific branching is already in place.
