20260509130457 Two clear answers: 1. What's in the test suite Three layers: Acceptance tests (Python/pytest): 41 files, 621 functions in tests/acceptance/ Unit tests (Lua/luaunit): 2 files in tests/unit/ — test_ass_alpha.lua, test_utf8.lua IPC harness: tests/ipc/mpv_session.py + tests/ipc/mpv_ipc.py — starts a real mpv process for integration tests, driven by conftest fixtures The Lua unit tests are run via tests/run_unit.lua, a standalone runner separate from mpv itself. 2. Do they affect normal operation? No. The separation is clean: The entire tests/ tree is Python — mpv never touches it. tests/run_unit.lua is a standalone script, not auto-loaded by mpv. The only test code that lives inside scripts/lls_core.lua is 28 lls-test-* script-message listeners (lines ~7921–8131). These are passive — mp.register_script_message just installs a named handler. Unless something explicitly sends lls-test-bind-seek, lls-test-set-cursor, etc. over the IPC socket, they never execute. During normal playback nobody sends those messages, so they're completely inert. No conditional guards around them, no startup side-effects, no hotkeys added — just dormant closures with negligible memory cost.
