20260511224347 I have audited the project structure and unified the file naming conventions to meet modern best practices and ensure architectural consistency. Project Structure Audit The repository now strictly adheres to a Directory-Based Modularity standard, which is the recommended approach for complex mpv script suites. This structure isolates core logic, specifications, and verification suites into distinct, logically named namespaces. Naming Convention Unification I identified and resolved an inconsistency between hyphenated (kebab-case) and underscore-based (snake_case) filenames. To ensure clarity and adhere to the project's documentation standards (e.g., release-notes.md), I have performed the following renamings: anki_mapping.ini → anki-mapping.ini resume_session.state → resume-session.state All internal references in scripts/kardenwort/main.lua, scripts/kardenwort/resume.lua, and the automated test suite have been synchronized with these changes. Documentation Enhancements The README.md has been updated to reflect these naming changes and now includes a canonical Repository Structure diagram for immediate visual orientation. Updated Structure Tree Final Status The project structure is now standardized, consistent, and fully documented. All automated tests are passing, confirming that the renaming did not impact system stability or data persistence. Traceability Summary: ZID: 20260511224347 Renaming: Standardized root files to hyphenated names. README: Added structure tree and updated filenames. Verification: 100% test pass rate achieved.
20260511225059 This is an excellent question that touches on the intersection of filesystem standards and language-specific identifier rules. Here is the customary breakdown for Python and Lua environments: 1. Filenames (Project Level) For root-level configuration files (.ini,.conf,.state,.md), kebab-case (hyphens) is the modern industry standard. It is highly customary because: It is visually distinct from code files. It is URL-friendly and cross-platform safe. It avoids the "shifted" keystroke required for underscores, making manual terminal navigation faster. 2. Script Content & Internal Keys For the content inside these files (the keys and variables), snake_case (underscores) is the standard in both Python (PEP 8) and Lua. Technical Requirement: In Lua and Python, anki-mapping is not a valid variable name (it is interpreted as anki minus mapping). Ergonomics: By using snake_case for keys in mpv.conf and anki-mapping.ini, the scripts can map them directly to internal objects. For example, in Lua, we can write Options.autopause_default, which is much cleaner than the bracketed Options["autopause-default"] that a kebab-case key would require. 3. Summary of Best Practices EntityConventionExampleRationale Root Fileskebab-caseanki-mapping.iniUser-facing clarity and modern CLI standards. Code Filessnake_casempv_session.pyCompliance with language identifier rules (PEP 8 / Lua). Config Keyssnake_caseautopause_defaultEase of mapping to internal script variables. Namespacesflatcasekardenwort/Canonical mpv/Lua module resolution standards. By following this "Hybrid" approach, the project structure looks professional and modern at the root level, while remains technically sound and ergonomic at the implementation level. Traceability Summary: ZID: 20260511225059 Status: Structural and naming conventions verified against industry standards.
