20260513125508 **Clarification**: I did not add anything to the settings file - I **removed** a duplicate key that was causing the JSON error. ### What Was Removed (Duplicate): ```json // REMOVED (line 272 - duplicate key): // "terminal.integrated.defaultProfile.windows": "Windows PowerShell", ``` ### What Remains (Corrected Section): ```json // Lines 220-226 - Correct terminal configuration "terminal.integrated.profiles.windows": { "PowerShell": { "source": "PowerShell", "args": ["-NoProfile", "-ExecutionPolicy", "Bypass"] } }, "terminal.integrated.defaultProfile.windows": "PowerShell", ``` ### Summary of Changes: | Action | Line | Key | Value | Status | |--------|------|-----|-------|--------| | **Kept** | 226 | `terminal.integrated.defaultProfile.windows` | `"PowerShell"` | ✅ Correct - matches profile name | | **Removed** | 272 | `terminal.integrated.defaultProfile.windows` | `"Windows PowerShell"` | ❌ Duplicate - didn't match profile | The fix removed the duplicate key at line 272. The value `"Windows PowerShell"` was incorrect because the profile is defined with the name `"PowerShell"`, not `"Windows PowerShell"`. Keeping `"PowerShell"` ensures the terminal correctly uses the profile with the custom arguments (`-NoProfile`, `-ExecutionPolicy Bypass`).
