20260514115450 x **Findings (full review, ordered by severity)** 1. **Critical: activation source is still boundary-biased to the previous subtitle in the exact path you reported.** The new resolver in [main.lua:6109](u:\voothi\20260308110646-kardenwort-mpv\scripts\kardenwort\main.lua:6109) calls `get_center_index(...)` live-first, but `get_center_index` itself is sticky/index-biased via `FSM.ACTIVE_IDX` logic in [main.lua:714](u:\voothi\20260308110646-kardenwort-mpv\scripts\kardenwort\main.lua:714) and overlap/tolerance checks in [main.lua:741](u:\voothi\20260308110646-kardenwort-mpv\scripts\kardenwort\main.lua:741) and [main.lua:754](u:\voothi\20260308110646-kardenwort-mpv\scripts\kardenwort\main.lua:754). Result: at subtitle boundaries, the intent snapshot can still resolve to the previous index, so `UP` activates on the previous subtitle exactly. 2. **High: follow-state context is destroyed before snapshot resolution.** In [main.lua:6173](u:\voothi\20260308110646-kardenwort-mpv\scripts\kardenwort\main.lua:6173), `DW_FOLLOW_PLAYER` is set to `false` before resolving navigation intent context. This removes useful “was-following-current” context for null activation and makes boundary arbitration less stable. 3. **High: null activation can legally fall through to previous line if first current-line pick fails once.** In [main.lua:6229](u:\voothi\20260308110646-kardenwort-mpv\scripts\kardenwort\main.lua:6229)–[main.lua:6250](u:\voothi\20260308110646-kardenwort-mpv\scripts\kardenwort\main.lua:6250), first activation scans from current line but can continue to neighbors when token pick returns `-1`. That creates the visible “lag/jump to previous” behavior even when intent was current-line activation. 4. **Medium: one test helper is semantically wrong for event-aware word navigation.** In [main.lua:8662](u:\voothi\20260308110646-kardenwort-mpv\scripts\kardenwort\main.lua:8662), `cmd_dw_word_move` receives `ctrl` as 3rd arg, but function expects an event table (see [main.lua:6263](u:\voothi\20260308110646-kardenwort-mpv\scripts\kardenwort\main.lua:6263)). This weakens diagnostics and can hide event-order defects during scripted checks. **Conclusion** You are right: the `UP` lag/jump is **not solved** yet. The current implementation still mixes “sticky playback index semantics” with “activation source semantics” in boundary windows. If you want, next step is a surgical patch in 3 points: 1. split activation-source resolver from sticky `get_center_index` path, 2. resolve intent before flipping follow-state, 3. hard-lock first null `UP/DOWN` activation to current resolved line (no neighbor fallback on first activation).
