20260515111254 The link is completely automatic and based on the Command Name. You don't need any extra IDs or special annotations to "connect" them! How it "Links" for you: The script uses the command itself as the bridge. As long as the command in the @help tag matches the command in the binding, it works perfectly. Example of the best way to write it: properties # @help: kardenwort/smart-space | Smart Space (Hold=Play) | SPACE SPACE script-binding kardenwort/smart-space Why this is enough: Implicit Linking: The script sees kardenwort/smart-space in the comment and says "Aha, whenever I see a key bound to this command, I will use this description." Order Doesn't Matter: You can put the @help line anywhere in the file, but for your own sanity, I recommend putting it directly above the keybinding. Global Effect: If you bind the same command to 5 different keys, the HUD will find all 5 keys and use that single @help description for all of them automatically. Verdict: It is unnecessary to do anything else. Just make sure the "Command" part of the @help tag matches the "Command" you are binding to your keys!
