20260515184543 No, this distribution does not violate your rights under the MIT license, nor does it conflict with mpv's license (GPL/LGPL). Why this is safe and compliant: MIT Permissiveness: The MIT license is highly permissive and compatible with almost all other licenses, including the GPL. It allows you to bundle, redistribute, and even sell the software, as long as the original copyright notice and permission notice are preserved. Aggregation vs. Derivative Work: By distributing a ZIP file containing both your code and mpv, you are performing what is known as "mere aggregation". Your MIT code and the GPL mpv code remain separate entities that interact through standard interfaces (scripts and command-line). This means your code does not "catch" the GPL license; it remains 100% yours under MIT. mpv Compliance: We have fulfilled the primary requirements for redistributing mpv binaries by: Adding a Third-party Licenses section to the README.md. Providing a link to the official mpv copyright and license source. Including the bundled documentation directory where applicable. Conclusion: You retain all your rights to the Kardenwort source code under the MIT license. The "Full" distribution is a valid and legally sound way to provide a convenient, zero-config experience for your users. I have logged this verification under the latest implementation ZID.
